ngDriver.failureMessage)\\n    } finally {\\n      DriverManager.deregisterDriver(driver)\\n    }\\n  }\\n}\\n\\nobject DoobieCoreFromDriverManagerFailingDriver {\\n  val url: String = \\\"jdbc:doobie-core-from-driver-manager-test\\\"\\n  val failureMessage: String = \\\"driver was loaded and asked to connect\\\"\\n}\\n\\nclass DoobieCoreFromDriverManagerFailingDriver extends Driver {\\n  override def connect(url: String, info: Properties): Connection = {\\n    if (acceptsURL(url)) {\\n      throw new SQLException(DoobieCoreFromDriverManagerFailingDriver.failureMessage)\\n    }\\n    null\\n  }\\n\\n  override def acceptsURL(url: String): Boolean =\\n    DoobieCoreFromDriverManagerFailingDriver.url == url\\n\\n  override def getPropertyInfo(url: String, info: Properties): Array[DriverPropertyInfo] =\\n    Array.empty[DriverPropertyInfo]\\n\\n  override def getMajorVersion: Int = 1\\n\\n  override def getMinorVersion: Int = 0\\n\\n  override def jdbcCompliant(): Boolean = false\\n\\n  override def getParentLogger: Logger = Logger.getGlobal\\n}\\n\"}]}\n1453:[recv] {\"type\": \"message_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Investigating dynamic coverage issues**\\n\\nI'm exploring issues with dynamic coverage tracks in a Doobie test class. The previous attempt might not have compiled or run due to an invalid result.swap.getOrElse. I wonder if the left type as Unit creates problems when expected to be Throwable. Another thought is that the native image could lack reflection metadata for `java.lang.String`. Even though `Class.forName` on existing classes should work, it seems there’s a possibility it didn’t get recorded due to failed reflection calls. Should I use a real JDBC driver since Doobie core doesn't include H2?\\n\\n**Exploring test dependency options**\\n\\nI’m considering adding a test dependency since the rules don’t forbid it. It might be beneficial to create a better public API using `fromDriverManager` with the driver \\\"org.h2.Driver\\\" and the URL \\\"jdbc:h2:mem:...\\\". I could also add `testImplementation com.h2database:h2`, but my focus should be on the active class. H2’s native image compatibility intrigues me, especially concerning metadata and dynamic class loading. It might be simpler to implement our own `java.sql.Driver` as a test source. I wonder if `Class.forName` needs metadata for the test driver class to succeed.\\n\\n**Clarifying the driver initialization process**\\n\\nI can explicitly reference the class to ensure it gets included, but the method call still needs to be dynamic. I need to make sure that `DriverManager` can return a connection if the driver is registered successfully. To avoid requiring a real connection, I could use a custom driver that's registered via the class's static initialization. However, using Scala's companion object for static initialization could be tricky. It seems that calling `Class.forName(driver)` should initialize and register the driver appropriately.\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_07804db651c470730169fafa68e7908193a90525511fd270e7\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABp-vrwHYVSCHKoHqVRVtofOJ6RfdWQTuwWXeXZAgoZWv6772O0Oo6v0Lg1VYngbHtKMwV5BaXreCUiQtz4cc6632eMNtCes0XwpNsYMy3Jau2-Oc9Yk37VhRwogmdGPC11vm0mjEdkxCb_hvKzGKW6x35LVnXLE4HMahrPCQTpvlZZ68JuruvHUoSkg-WenOCI6ar7lptJU59mhzASM8lvetI0dQ7NHc6Wl7OKmv0mHbFNQT_3ulJqJJOVImo9hW4DzuQmDqRQwvaJP8FqfJ3jYrzDhA-2xzAeWXe0X1lHll_ZbGihGXfG7rbgZoKgfOoK1OwNGLxE9qgbJmMHXx-eTaDZQyQ_Urbs5m-EjMRBPfOO2fDwUeDjECsQqKSegZ0QqRzaa4Qs3i1kK3W_PzVTXRSk-j60dRoldj1MwV7rAO7R7J4i2xhmjdKgzjaeQTJBSipCPU807n0CazZmJeNaXqrjBnCeZoPJqGT6Yyx6SgOq_-vFXbdm1ERh5s0EEE549CRrSeWWkM-FaehQ2fvoi0p6coymGsO3HQHlBq_w-CY0BogmhLIXxx3GnWvUNPf-FCMj1SGndrtVW5MDeDWONd66Sr5YfbmyFJ63NVwJB65MKYkf-a0TKm97dai_ibB4V71OlWblZRoo4niFd8gjjVzxjk63lcmc0Mdm1fkqrm2IslxAkCJFbwJNRG0K8JcCoJPfF9V0BQKRaktLhayeE8XwmshZOynKl_trnfoPRzI7kOQWbvKe5AnoDBO7y12CACrx9uOcTYDYB9HtIByzuZ8V