summary\\\":[{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Investigating dynamic coverage issues**\\\\n\\\\nI'm exploring issues with dynamic coverage tracks in a Doobie test class. The previous attempt might not have compiled or run due to an invalid result.swap.getOrElse. I wonder if the left type as Unit creates problems when expected to be Throwable. Another thought is that the native image could lack reflection metadata for `java.lang.String`. Even though `Class.forName` on existing classes should work, it seems there’s a possibility it didn’t get recorded due to failed reflection calls. Should I use a real JDBC driver since Doobie core doesn't include H2?\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Exploring test dependency options**\\\\n\\\\nI’m considering adding a test dependency since the rules don’t forbid it. It might be beneficial to create a better public API using `fromDriverManager` with the driver \\\\\\\"org.h2.Driver\\\\\\\" and the URL \\\\\\\"jdbc:h2:mem:...\\\\\\\". I could also add `testImplementation com.h2database:h2`, but my focus should be on the active class. H2’s native image compatibility intrigues me, especially concerning metadata and dynamic class loading. It might be simpler to implement our own `java.sql.Driver` as a test source. I wonder if `Class.forName` needs metadata for the test driver class to succeed.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Clarifying the driver initialization process**\\\\n\\\\nI can explicitly reference the class to ensure it gets included, but the method call still needs to be dynamic. I need to make sure that `DriverManager` can return a connection if the driver is registered successfully. To avoid requiring a real connection, I could use a custom driver that's registered via the class's static initialization. However, using Scala's companion object for static initialization could be tricky. It seems that calling `Class.forName(driver)` should initialize and register the driver appropriately.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_RJa17QdwB4JG9mgTAfvf44SW|fc_07804db651c470730169fafaf01cc08193a8975196177b2c65\", \"name\": \"edit\", \"arguments\": {\"path\": \"tests/src/org.tpolecat/doobie-core_3/0.13.4/src/test/scala/org_tpolecat/doobie_core_3/TransactorInnerTransactorInnerFromDriverManagerTest.scala\", \"edits\": [{\"oldText\": \"import java.sql.SQLException\\nimport scala.concurrent.ExecutionContext\\n\\nclass TransactorInnerTransactorInnerFromDriverManagerTest {\\n  private implicit val contextShift: ContextShift[IO] = IO.contextShift(ExecutionContext.global)\\n  private val blocker: Blocker = Blocker.liftExecutionContext(ExecutionContext.global)\\n\\n  @Test\\n  @Timeout(10)\\n  def fromDriverManagerLoadsDriverClassWhenOpeningConnection(): Unit = {\\n    val xa: Transactor.Aux[IO, Unit] =\\n      Transactor.fromDriverManager[IO](\\n        \\\"java.lang.String\\\",\\n        \\\"jdbc:doobie-core-test:missing-database\\\",\\n        blocker\\n      )\\n\\n    val result: Either[Throwable, Unit] =\\n      xa.connect(xa.kernel).use(_ => IO.unit).attempt.unsafeRunSync()\\n\\n    val failure: Throwable =\\n      result.swap.getOrElse(new AssertionError(\\\"Expected connection acquisition to fail\\\"))\\n\\n    assertThat(failure).isInstanceOf(classOf[SQLException])\\n    assertThat(failure.getMessage).contains(\\\"No suitable driver\\\")\\n  }\\n}\\n\", \"newText\": \"import java.sql.Connection\\nimport java.sql.Driver\\nimport java.sql.DriverManager\\nimport java.sql.DriverPropertyInfo\\nimport java.sql.SQLException\\nimport java.util.Properties\\nimport java.util.logging.Logger\\nimport scala.concurrent.ExecutionContext\\n\\nclass TransactorInnerTransactorInnerFromDriverManagerTest {\\n  private implicit val contextShift: ContextShift[IO] = IO.contextShift(ExecutionContext.global)\\n  private val blocker: Blocker = Blocker.liftExecutionContext(ExecutionContext.global)\\n\\n  @Test\\n  @Timeout(10)\\n  def fromD